RESEARCH DEPARTMENT
REPORT
REPORT NO: RDR094/00
AUTHOR: AAJ GOLDSMITH
TITLE: CERAMIC-ON-METAL HIP SIMULATOR TEST (HS0005)
Comparative test with Ultima 28mm Metal-on-Metal (HS0003)
DESCRIPTION OF COMPONENT/MATERIAL:
(REFERENCE LISTS 1 AND 2 )
HS0005: Articul/eze alumina ceramic head, 28mm +5mm, cat. no. 1365-74-000. (n=4).
HS0004: Articul/eze zirconia head, 28mm +5mm, cat. no. 1365-44-000. (n=3)
HS0003: Ultima metal-on-metal head, 28mm +3.5mm, cat. no. 859851. (n=3).
All 10 heads matched to Ultima metal-on-metal std inserts, cat. no. 859845.
Ultima: wrought CoCr ASTM F1537, JJP RMS65/05, low carbon heads (<0.07%C), high carbon cups (>0.2%C).
TEST PROTOCOL:
Applied Research Test Protocols: TP018-022 (wear testing and measurements)
SUMMARY/ABSTRACT:
To evaluate the long-term wear performance of a novel ceramic-on-metal (CoM) hip bearing, a hip simulator wear test was
conducted to over 5 million cycles in Applied Research. The two articulating components in each case were both standard
approved products: a 28mm alumina head articulating against a cobalt chrome insert from the Ultima metal -on-metal (MoM) hip
system. Four pairs of this bearing were tested to 5 million cycles in hip simulator test HS0005. To provide comparative data and
further benchmark data for the Ultima MOM system, 3 pairs of Ultima MoM were tested (test HS0003). The Ultima test
completed 6.3 million cycles. Three pairs of standard zirconia heads were also matched with Ultima metal inserts (test HS0004)
and the results are reported here but, for reasons related to this specific head design rather than fundamental principles or the
materials, a direct comparison could not be made with the alumina-CoCr test.
Gravimetric analysis of wear was performed on heads and inserts throughout the test. Key parameters to evaluate were the
duration of the initial 'running-in' phase of higher wear, the magnitude of wear in this phase (volume of material lost) and
particularly the wear rate of the bearings once a steady-state phase of lower wear was attained. Diametral clearance is a key
design parameter for hard bearing combinations; the test components were matched prior to testing to produce a range of
diametral clearance. Average clearance was 58um for the COM and 61 um for the Ultima.
Wear measurements indicated a mean long-term wear rate for the COM of only 0.05mm'/10 cycles, compared to 0.40 mm/10
cycles for the Ultima. This is an 8-fold decrease. The COM also achieved this low wear rate after a very short period compared to
the Ultima such that the total wear, after running-in, was also an order of magnitude smaller. All wear occurred on the metal
insert, the alumina heads were not visibly damaged but some metal transfer was seen. Post-test surface analysis showed almost
no damage to the COM components.
The wear rate of the COM is comparable to, even better than ceramic-on-ceramic. Wear rates were not statistically different.
Previous data suggests similar metal debris characteristics to MoM. DePuy hold the patent for any CoM joint replacement. The
components are validated standard product. This exciting technology offers a further option in alternative bearing markets.

KEYWORDS:
ceramic-on-metal, hip simulator, HS0005, HS0003, Ultima, wear
